3. Third-Pass Findings That Sharpen the Verdict
Finding A — The README is more honest than the runtime phase matrix.
README says early software and points exact counts to generated runtime docs. That is good. The problem is that generated runtime docs use strong completion language: Phase 5 COMPLETE, Phase 6 COMPLETE, Phase 7 COMPLETE, Phase 8 ACTIVE, Phase 9 ACTIVE. Internally this may mean specific gates are implemented, but externally it reads like a mature platform. Recommendation: add a plain-language maturity interpretation beside the phase matrix.

Finding B — OpenClaw wording is now the largest perception-risk area.
Runtime state says Phase 9 ACTIVE with OpenClaw intelligence layer, iterative thinking loop, goal-based execution, execution memory, executor-backed mutation tools, parallel/chained execution, retry/circuit breaker, self-awareness context injection, and friendly personality. Even if gated, that sounds like autonomous agent behavior. Recommendation: describe OpenClaw as governed worker infrastructure, not as a broad autonomous intelligence layer.

Finding C — The architecture map is strong, but the hot path is concentrated.
REPO_MAP correctly tells reviewers to start with brain_server.py and session_handler.py. But those files are very large: 3,624 lines and 3,821 lines respectively. This increases merge risk, regression risk, cognitive load, and contributor onboarding difficulty.

Finding D — Docs reveal focus leakage.
docs/INDEX.md is useful, but the Website LLC and Demo Previews lanes inside the Nova docs index blur NovaLIS identity. They may be valuable for the owner, but they should not live in the main NovaLIS documentation spine if the repo is meant to attract users/contributors.

Finding E — The test suite is a major strength, but it does not equal product readiness.
The test directory breadth is impressive and supports the governance claims. But governance/routing tests do not prove a user can install, understand, and use the product easily. The repo needs a user-readiness checklist separate from test-pass status.

Finding F — Installation is still development-first.
QUICKSTART is clear, but it asks for Windows, Python, Ollama, a checkout directory, and optional environment variables. That is appropriate for developers, not general users. The repo has installer/start/stop surfaces, but the docs still position the practical path as a development checkout.

Finding G — The true differentiator is not “assistant”; it is “authority separation.”
This is the strongest product strategy: Nova should be positioned as a governed local assistant/control plane. Competing on “general AI assistant” is weak; competing on visible authority, ledgered actions, bounded execution, and local-first governance is credible.

