5. Claims Classification
Accurate Claims
• Nova separates conversation/reasoning from governed execution.
• Actions route through explicit governance components rather than direct free-running tool calls.
• Runtime truth docs are generated and intended to outrank stale manual claims.
• The system is source-available, local-first in design intent, and not a finished product.
• There is real test infrastructure around governance, executors, OpenClaw, phases, rendering, and simulation.
Overstated or Risky Claims
• Phase COMPLETE labels can be mistaken for user-ready product maturity.
• Phase 9 ACTIVE wording makes OpenClaw sound more autonomous than the project philosophy allows.
• “Friendly personality” and “self-awareness context injection” are risky phrases for a governance-first project; they invite misunderstanding.
• Active capability count does not indicate reliability, installability, or normal-user usefulness.
• “Built for operators” is true, but may conflict with consumer-assistant expectations.
Understated Strengths
• The repo map and generated runtime truth system are unusually mature for a solo/early project.
• The test hierarchy is broader than many small AI projects.
• The Business Source License positioning is intentional and clear.
• The project has a real path to differentiation through authority separation, not through generic chatbot features.
• The OpenClaw integration, if carefully bounded, could become a powerful governed-worker layer.
Missing or Weak Documentation
• A plain-language “What is actually user-ready today?” page.
• A capability maturity table: prototype / tested / user-ready / risky / disabled.
• A first-run troubleshooting guide with screenshots and expected local states.
• A “what OpenClaw can do safely today” document with examples and hard limits.
• A normal-user product page that avoids phase jargon.
