7. Third-Pass Strategic Recommendation
Nova should not add another major capability right now. The next highest-leverage milestone is a product-truth consolidation sprint: package, label, simplify, and prove what already exists. The project’s technical base is credible enough that the bottleneck has shifted from “can this architecture exist?” to “can a user understand and operate it safely?”

• P0 — Create USER_READY_STATUS.md: One page with three columns: Works Now, Experimental, Not Yet. No phase jargon. Link from README above roadmap links.
• P0 — Add capability maturity metadata: For every capability: enabled, tested, user-ready, requires key, requires local dependency, write-capable, confirmation-required, known limitations.
• P0 — Reword Phase 8/9 public language: Keep internal runtime labels if needed, but public docs should say “operator workflows active” and “governed OpenClaw worker runtime experimental.”
• P1 — Installer-first documentation: Make “download/start/health check/first safe command” the main path. Move Python checkout to Developer Setup.
• P1 — Hot-path extraction plan: Do not big-bang refactor. First add characterization tests; then extract static routes, settings endpoints, websocket command handlers, and capability adapters.
• P1 — Move non-core docs: Website LLC and preview docs should become separate project docs or an archive, not part of Nova’s main docs index.
• P2 — UX simplification: Default UI should show: chat, status, recent governed actions. Everything else behind details/advanced.
• P2 — Contributor onboarding: Add “first contribution path” and 5 small governance-safe issues.
8. Final Third-Pass Verdict
NovaLIS is not a toy. The governance model is real, the architecture is coherent, and the repo has enough tests and generated runtime truth to be taken seriously. The project is differentiated because it treats authority as a first-class engineering problem instead of letting tool use hide inside a chatbot loop.

The hard criticism: Nova is now at risk of becoming impressive but confusing. The repo has too many phase labels, too many active-sounding capability claims, and too much public roadmap energy compared with the amount of product-ready user experience. The next win is not more intelligence. The next win is clarity.

Best honest label today: advanced governed local-assistant prototype / early local AI control plane. Not consumer-ready. Not fake. Not finished. Very promising if disciplined.

